27c054dd-272c-42d5-bcc4-eb8bcb556e72	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	Is Homework Necessary?	education-opinion-is-homework-necessary	Many students spend hours doing homework every day. Some people believe homework helps students learn and practice, while others think it causes stress and takes away free time. What is your opinion on homework? Do you think it is necessary for students, or should schools reduce it? Explain your reasons.	Viß║┐t mß╗Öt b├ái luß║¡n n├¬u quan ─æiß╗âm cß╗ºa bß║ín vß╗ü viß╗çc l├ám b├ái tß║¡p vß╗ü nh├á. Bß║ín ngh─⌐ b├ái tß║¡p vß╗ü nh├á c├│ cß║ºn thiß║┐t cho hß╗ìc sinh kh├┤ng?	80	150	B1	OPINION	1	t	2026-07-14 19:06:03.294	2026-07-14 19:06:03.294	20	\N	0	I think homework is important, but schools should not give too much. Homework helps students remember what they learned in class. When I do homework, I practice new things and understand them better. For example, math homework helps me get good at numbers. However, too much homework makes students tired and stressed. They need time to relax, play, or spend with family. Sometimes, I have so much homework that I cannot do other fun activities. I believe a small amount of homework every day is good for learning, but a lot is bad for students' health and happiness. So, it should be balanced.
137765a2-71a3-4f2a-8a97-7a169b9e0286	a9107456-5182-4e8e-bf13-0adc4946b8fb	Eating for Health	health-sentence-eating-for-health	H├úy so s├ính thß╗▒c phß║⌐m l├ánh mß║ính v├á thß╗▒c phß║⌐m kh├┤ng l├ánh mß║ính. Bß║ín th╞░ß╗¥ng xuy├¬n ─ân nhß╗»ng loß║íi thß╗▒c phß║⌐m l├ánh mß║ính n├áo? C├│ nhß╗»ng loß║íi thß╗▒c phß║⌐m kh├┤ng l├ánh mß║ính n├áo bß║ín cß╗æ gß║»ng tr├ính kh├┤ng?	Compare healthy and unhealthy foods and discuss your food choices.	80	150	B1	SENTENCE	3	t	2026-07-16 19:00:58.853	2026-07-16 19:00:58.853	20	\N	0	Eating healthy food is essential for a good life. Healthy foods, like fruits, vegetables, and whole grains, give us energy and important nutrients. They help our body grow and stay strong. For example, I eat apples, bananas, and a lot of green vegetables every day. I also try to eat chicken or fish instead of red meat. On the other hand, unhealthy foods often contain a lot of sugar, salt, and bad fats. Examples include fast food, sugary drinks, and potato chips. These foods can make us gain weight and cause health problems if we eat them too often. I try to avoid soft drinks and limit my intake of fried foods. Choosing healthy options helps me feel better and keeps my body in good condition.
d7fc5aa1-2a5f-4c63-87ba-6d95cfa42234	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	Online Learning vs. Traditional Classroom	education-opinion-online-vs-traditional-learning	In recent years, online learning has become very popular. Some people prefer learning online because it is flexible, while others still believe that traditional classrooms are better. What is your opinion? Do you think online learning is better than traditional classroom learning, or is it the other way around? Support your view with reasons.	Thß║úo luß║¡n vß╗ü ╞░u v├á nh╞░ß╗úc ─æiß╗âm cß╗ºa viß╗çc hß╗ìc trß╗▒c tuyß║┐n so vß╗¢i hß╗ìc truyß╗ün thß╗æng v├á ─æ╞░a ra quan ─æiß╗âm c├í nh├ón.	80	150	B1	OPINION	2	t	2026-07-14 19:06:03.31	2026-07-14 19:06:03.31	20	\N	0	I think both online learning and traditional classroom learning have good points. Online learning is very convenient because you can study from home and choose your own time. This is good for people who work or live far from school. However, in a traditional classroom, you can ask the teacher questions easily and talk with your friends. This helps you understand difficult topics better and makes learning more fun. For me, I prefer traditional classroom learning. I like to be with other students and learn face-to-face with the teacher. It feels more engaging and I can focus better without distractions from home.
4d1b108e-f113-413d-a031-ad7ae70380ba	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	Should Schools Teach More Practical Skills?	education-opinion-schools-teach-practical-skills	Many schools focus a lot on academic subjects like math, science, and history. Some people argue that schools should also teach more practical skills, such as cooking, managing money, or basic car maintenance. What is your opinion? Do you think practical skills are as important as academic subjects, or even more important for students' future? Explain your viewpoint.	N├¬u quan ─æiß╗âm cß╗ºa bß║ín vß╗ü viß╗çc liß╗çu tr╞░ß╗¥ng hß╗ìc c├│ n├¬n tß║¡p trung nhiß╗üu h╞ín v├áo viß╗çc dß║íy c├íc kß╗╣ n─âng thß╗▒c tß║┐ cho hß╗ìc sinh kh├┤ng.	80	150	B1	OPINION	3	t	2026-07-14 19:06:03.327	2026-07-14 19:06:03.327	20	\N	0	I strongly believe that schools should teach more practical skills. Academic subjects are important for knowledge, but practical skills help us in daily life. For example, learning how to cook or manage money is very useful when we become adults. Many students finish school but don't know how to do simple things for themselves. If schools taught these skills, students would be better prepared for life after graduation. It would help them become more independent and responsible. Academic knowledge is good, but without practical skills, it can be hard to live well. So, I think practical skills should have a bigger place in the school curriculum.
bb62fdeb-e811-4772-b2bc-eb361bd2e99b	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	Are Good Grades the Most Important Thing?	education-opinion-grades-most-important	In many schools, getting good grades is seen as the most important goal. Students often feel pressure to achieve high marks. However, some people believe that true learning and personal development are more important than just grades. What is your opinion? Do you think good grades are the most important thing in education, or are there other things that matter more? Give reasons for your view.	Thß║úo luß║¡n vß╗ü tß║ºm quan trß╗ìng cß╗ºa ─æiß╗âm sß╗æ trong gi├ío dß╗Ñc v├á liß╗çu ch├║ng c├│ phß║úi l├á yß║┐u tß╗æ quan trß╗ìng nhß║Ñt hay kh├┤ng.	80	150	B1	OPINION	4	t	2026-07-14 19:06:03.339	2026-07-14 19:06:03.339	20	\N	0	I don't think good grades are the most important thing in education, even though they are certainly useful. Of course, good grades can help you get into a good university or find a job. But learning new things, understanding the world, and developing skills like critical thinking or teamwork are much more valuable. Sometimes, students focus only on memorizing for tests to get high grades, but they don't truly understand the subject. True learning means you can use your knowledge in real life. Also, things like creativity, kindness, and problem-solving skills are not measured by grades but are very important for a successful and happy life. So, I believe learning and personal growth are more important than just getting high marks.
6e34e05d-5310-46c3-8868-673a28a71801	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	Technology in Classrooms: Help or Harm?	education-opinion-technology-classroom	Technology like tablets, computers, and the internet is now common in many classrooms. Some people think technology greatly improves learning and makes lessons more interesting. Others worry that it can distract students and reduce face-to-face interaction. What is your opinion? Do you think technology in classrooms is mostly helpful or mostly harmful for students' education? Explain your reasons.	Chia sß║╗ quan ─æiß╗âm cß╗ºa bß║ín vß╗ü viß╗çc sß╗¡ dß╗Ñng c├┤ng nghß╗ç (m├íy t├¡nh bß║úng, ─æiß╗çn thoß║íi, internet) trong lß╗¢p hß╗ìc.	80	150	B1	OPINION	5	t	2026-07-14 19:06:03.349	2026-07-14 19:06:03.349	20	\N	0	I believe technology in classrooms can be very helpful if used correctly. For example, using tablets to search for information or watch educational videos can make lessons more fun and interactive. It helps students learn in different ways and prepares them for a digital world. Also, online tools can help teachers explain difficult topics visually. However, there is a risk of distraction. Students might use devices for games or social media instead of learning. Teachers need to manage technology carefully to make sure students focus. Overall, I think the benefits outweigh the risks. Technology can be a powerful tool to improve education, but it needs good guidance from teachers.
7855ca6e-4a22-4dbc-b52b-96bbcbe069be	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	The Math Challenge	education-story-the-math-challenge	H├úy kß╗â mß╗Öt c├óu chuyß╗çn vß╗ü mß╗Öt hß╗ìc sinh ─æ├ú gß║╖p kh├│ kh─ân trong mß╗Öt m├┤n hß╗ìc ß╗ƒ tr╞░ß╗¥ng (v├¡ dß╗Ñ: To├ín, L├╜, H├│a, Tiß║┐ng Anh). H├úy m├┤ tß║ú cß║úm x├║c cß╗ºa hß╗ì v├á c├ích hß╗ì ─æ├ú nß╗ù lß╗▒c ─æß╗â cß║úi thiß╗çn, cuß╗æi c├╣ng ─æß║ít ─æ╞░ß╗úc kß║┐t quß║ú tß╗æt.	Write a story about a student who struggled with a difficult subject and how they finally succeeded.	80	150	B1	STORY	1	t	2026-07-14 19:06:19.452	2026-07-14 19:06:19.452	20	\N	0	Minh always found math difficult. Numbers confused him, and he often felt lost in class. One day, he got a very low score on a math test. He felt sad and wanted to give up. However, his teacher, Ms. Lien, saw his potential. She offered to help him after school twice a week. At first, Minh was shy, but Ms. Lien was patient and explained things clearly. She used real-life examples to make math fun. Minh started practicing more at home too. Slowly, he began to understand. His confidence grew with each small success. In the next test, he scored much higher! He realized that hard work and a good teacher can make a big difference. He was proud of himself for not giving up.
52ac4817-c387-4b2c-b1fc-dca5228ccd75	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	The Unexpected Lesson	education-story-the-unexpected-lesson	H├úy kß╗â mß╗Öt c├óu chuyß╗çn vß╗ü mß╗Öt hß╗ìc sinh ─æ├ú hß╗ìc ─æ╞░ß╗úc mß╗Öt b├ái hß╗ìc qu├╜ gi├í kh├┤ng phß║úi tß╗½ s├ích vß╗ƒ hay thß║ºy c├┤, m├á tß╗½ mß╗Öt trß║úi nghiß╗çm b├¬n ngo├ái lß╗¢p hß╗ìc (v├¡ dß╗Ñ: tham gia c├óu lß║íc bß╗Ö, gi├║p ─æß╗í ai ─æ├│, mß╗Öt chuyß║┐n ─æi thß╗▒c tß║┐).	Write a story about a valuable lesson a student learned from an experience outside of the classroom.	80	150	B1	STORY	2	t	2026-07-14 19:06:19.46	2026-07-14 19:06:19.46	20	\N	0	Last summer, my friend Mai decided to volunteer at a local animal shelter. She loved animals but had never worked with them before. Her first few days were tough. She had to clean cages, prepare food, and learn how to handle different animals. Sometimes, the work was dirty and tiring. One afternoon, a small, scared puppy arrived. Mai spent hours gently talking to it and offering food. Slowly, the puppy started to trust her. Mai realized that patience and kindness were very important. She learned more about responsibility and empathy than she ever did in her biology class. When the puppy found a new home, Mai felt a great sense of achievement. It was a lesson she would never forget.
b191db88-2b34-4e33-bd83-3ded086e5fdb	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	My Inspiring Teacher	education-story-my-inspiring-teacher	H├úy kß╗â mß╗Öt c├óu chuyß╗çn vß╗ü mß╗Öt gi├ío vi├¬n m├á bß║ín hoß║╖c mß╗Öt hß╗ìc sinh kh├íc tß╗½ng biß║┐t, ng╞░ß╗¥i ─æ├ú c├│ ß║únh h╞░ß╗ƒng t├¡ch cß╗▒c ─æß║╖c biß╗çt. M├┤ tß║ú ─æiß╗üu g├¼ ─æ├ú khiß║┐n ng╞░ß╗¥i gi├ío vi├¬n ─æ├│ trß╗ƒ n├¬n ─æ├íng nhß╗¢ v├á hß╗ì ─æ├ú gi├║p ─æß╗í hß╗ìc sinh nh╞░ thß║┐ n├áo.	Write a story about a teacher who had a profound positive impact on a student's life or learning experience.	80	150	B1	STORY	3	t	2026-07-14 19:06:19.465	2026-07-14 19:06:19.465	20	\N	0	When I was in primary school, I had a history teacher named Mr. Binh. He wasn't just a teacher; he was a storyteller. Instead of reading from textbooks, he would tell us amazing stories about ancient civilizations and heroes. His eyes would light up, and he would use different voices for historical figures. His lessons were never boring. Because of Mr. Binh, I fell in love with history. He made me curious and encouraged me to read more books outside of class. He always said, "History is not just about dates; it's about people and their lives." He taught me to think critically and to understand the past. Thanks to him, history became my favorite subject, and I still remember his stories clearly today.
78788c3f-372e-459d-b943-8b740e02391a	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	A Fresh Start	education-story-a-fresh-start	H├úy kß╗â mß╗Öt c├óu chuyß╗çn vß╗ü ng├áy ─æß║ºu ti├¬n cß╗ºa mß╗Öt hß╗ìc sinh hoß║╖c sinh vi├¬n tß║íi mß╗Öt tr╞░ß╗¥ng hß╗ìc hoß║╖c ─æß║íi hß╗ìc mß╗¢i. M├┤ tß║ú cß║úm gi├íc cß╗ºa hß╗ì (hß╗ôi hß╗Öp, lo lß║»ng, h├áo hß╗⌐ng) v├á nhß╗»ng ─æiß╗üu mß╗¢i mß║╗ hß╗ì ─æ├ú trß║úi nghiß╗çm trong ng├áy ─æ├│.	Write a story about a student's first day at a new school or university, including their feelings and new experiences.	80	150	B1	STORY	4	t	2026-07-14 19:06:19.471	2026-07-14 19:06:19.471	20	\N	0	Linh woke up early, her heart beating fast. Today was her first day at university, and she felt a mix of excitement and nervousness. She walked into the large campus, seeing so many new faces. Finding her classroom was a bit challenging, but she finally made it. Her first lecture was about literature. The professor was interesting, and Linh took many notes. During the break, she sat alone at first, feeling a little shy. Then, a girl named Hoa smiled and invited her to sit with her friends. They talked about their hometowns and their dreams. Linh felt much better after that. She realized that making new friends would be an important part of her new journey. It was a big day, full of new beginnings.
dfed4450-c483-4b61-9df3-1c0974eb5dee	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	The Science Fair Project	education-story-the-science-fair-project	H├úy kß╗â mß╗Öt c├óu chuyß╗çn vß╗ü mß╗Öt dß╗▒ ├ín hß╗ìc tß║¡p (v├¡ dß╗Ñ: dß╗▒ ├ín khoa hß╗ìc, b├ái thuyß║┐t tr├¼nh nh├│m, l├ám b├ío t╞░ß╗¥ng) m├á bß║ín hoß║╖c mß╗Öt hß╗ìc sinh n├áo ─æ├│ ─æ├ú thß╗▒c hiß╗çn ß╗ƒ tr╞░ß╗¥ng. M├┤ tß║ú qu├í tr├¼nh l├ám dß╗▒ ├ín, nhß╗»ng thß╗¡ th├ích gß║╖p phß║úi v├á kß║┐t quß║ú cuß╗æi c├╣ng.	Write a story about a student's experience with a school project, perhaps a science fair or a group presentation.	80	150	B1	STORY	5	t	2026-07-14 19:06:19.479	2026-07-14 19:06:19.479	20	\N	0	Last year, my class had a big science project: creating a model of the solar system. I was in a group with three other students: An, Lan, and Tung. We decided to make our planets out of colorful clay and hang them from a large cardboard box. At first, we were very excited. However, we soon faced challenges. An wanted to use bright colors, while Lan preferred more realistic tones. Also, attaching the planets with string was harder than we thought; they kept falling down! We learned to compromise and work together. Tung was good at making the orbits, and I helped with the labels. Finally, after many hours, our solar system looked fantastic. We presented it to the class, feeling proud of our teamwork. We learned about space and also about working with others.
a6aae5af-397b-495f-bafa-bd427d80a653	bf13dc19-fde0-4940-89f4-205214ee9268	Student Enrollment in Different Faculties (2000 & 2020)	education-ielts-task1-student-enrollment-faculties	The bar chart below shows the number of students enrolled in four different faculties (Arts, Science, Business, and Engineering) at a university in 2000 and 2020. Summarize the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.	Hß╗ìc vi├¬n sß║╜ m├┤ tß║ú mß╗Öt biß╗âu ─æß╗ô cß╗Öt so s├ính sß╗æ l╞░ß╗úng sinh vi├¬n ghi danh v├áo c├íc khoa kh├íc nhau tß║íi mß╗Öt tr╞░ß╗¥ng ─æß║íi hß╗ìc trong hai n─âm ri├¬ng biß╗çt.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_1	1	t	2026-07-14 19:06:40.831	2026-07-14 19:06:40.831	20	\N	0	The bar chart shows student numbers across four faculties (Arts, Science, Business, and Engineering) in 2000 and 2020. Overall, student enrollment increased in most faculties from 2000 to 2020, with Engineering seeing the biggest rise.\n\nIn 2000, Arts had the highest enrollment with 300 students, followed by Business with 250. Science had 200 students, and Engineering had the fewest at 150. By 2020, Engineering enrollment significantly increased to 400 students, becoming the most popular faculty. Business also grew to 350 students. Arts saw a small increase to 320, while Science remained almost the same at 210 students. The total number of students in these faculties clearly went up over the two decades.
9e40fc34-3d4d-4a38-bb9e-429a78e516ab	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	H├ánh ─æß╗Öng xanh mß╗ùi ng├áy	environment-sentence-green-actions-daily	Ngh─⌐ vß╗ü nhß╗»ng viß╗çc bß║ín c├│ thß╗â l├ám h├áng ng├áy ─æß╗â gi├║p m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng. V├¡ dß╗Ñ: tiß║┐t kiß╗çm ─æiß╗çn, giß║úm r├íc thß║úi nhß╗▒a, ─æi bß╗Ö thay v├¼ l├íi xe. H├úy viß║┐t mß╗Öt ─æoß║ín v─ân ngß║»n (80-150 tß╗½) m├┤ tß║ú nhß╗»ng h├ánh ─æß╗Öng n├áy v├á tß║íi sao ch├║ng quan trß╗ìng.	Viß║┐t vß╗ü nhß╗»ng h├ánh ─æß╗Öng nhß╗Å bß║ín c├│ thß╗â l├ám mß╗ùi ng├áy ─æß╗â bß║úo vß╗ç m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng.	80	150	B1	SENTENCE	1	t	2026-07-16 19:02:09.911	2026-07-16 19:02:09.911	20	\N	0	Protecting our environment is very important, and we can all help. One simple action is to save electricity. We should turn off lights and unplug chargers when we are not using them. Another good habit is to reduce plastic waste. We can use reusable bags for shopping and carry a water bottle instead of buying plastic ones. Also, choosing to walk or cycle instead of driving a car helps to reduce air pollution. These small actions make a big difference for our planet. They keep our air clean and our world healthy for everyone.
