992295cf-c724-4f06-8be9-c37c43546eea	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	A Message from the Future	environment-story-a-message-from-the-future	Bß║ín c├│ mß╗Öt giß║Ñc m╞í hoß║╖c bß║ín nhß║¡n ─æ╞░ß╗úc mß╗Öt th├┤ng ─æiß╗çp kß╗│ lß║í tß╗½ t╞░╞íng lai, kß╗â vß╗ü t├¼nh trß║íng m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng cß╗ºa thß║┐ giß╗¢i ch├║ng ta. M├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng trong giß║Ñc m╞í ─æ├│ tr├┤ng nh╞░ thß║┐ n├áo? C├│ ─æiß╗üu g├¼ ─æ├íng lo ngß║íi hay hy vß╗ìng kh├┤ng? Kß╗â lß║íi c├óu chuyß╗çn vß╗ü giß║Ñc m╞í/th├┤ng ─æiß╗çp ─æ├│ v├á n├│ ─æ├ú thay ─æß╗òi c├ích bß║ín ngh─⌐ vß╗ü viß╗çc bß║úo vß╗ç m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng hiß╗çn tß║íi nh╞░ thß║┐ n├áo.	Write a short story about a character who receives a message or has a dream about the environment in the future, inspiring them to take action today.	80	150	B1	STORY	5	t	2026-07-16 19:03:21.414	2026-07-16 19:03:21.414	20	\N	0	Last night, I had a very strange dream. I was in a big city, but it wasn't like our city today. The air was very thick and gray, and I could barely see the sun. There were no trees, only tall, dark buildings. The streets were full of garbage, and no one seemed to care. I felt very sad and scared in my dream. Then, I saw a small child crying because they couldn't find a clean flower. When I woke up, I still felt worried. It was just a dream, but it felt so real. It made me think about our planet and what we are doing to it. I decided that I want to do more to protect our environment, starting today. Every small action helps.
56ed1c4f-aa18-45dd-861a-2ab0b6a6cb6a	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Xu h╞░ß╗¢ng L╞░ß╗úng Kh├¡ Thß║úi CO2	environment-ielts-task-1-co2-emissions-trend-graph	The line graph below illustrates the amount of carbon dioxide (CO2) emitted by a particular country from 1990 to 2020.\n\n[Imagine a line graph where CO2 emissions start at 300 million tonnes in 1990, rise steadily to 500 million tonnes by 2010, and then slightly decrease to 450 million tonnes by 2020.]\n\nSummarize the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant. Write at least 80 words.	M├┤ tß║ú biß╗âu ─æß╗ô ─æ╞░ß╗¥ng thß╗â hiß╗çn xu h╞░ß╗¢ng l╞░ß╗úng kh├¡ thß║úi CO2 cß╗ºa mß╗Öt quß╗æc gia qua c├íc n─âm tß╗½ 1990 ─æß║┐n 2020.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_1	1	t	2026-07-16 19:03:44.193	2026-07-16 19:03:44.193	20	\N	0	The line graph shows changes in CO2 emissions from one country between 1990 and 2020.\n\nOverall, CO2 emissions in this country generally increased over the period, although there was a slight decrease at the end.\n\nIn 1990, the country emitted about 300 million tonnes of CO2. This figure rose steadily, reaching approximately 400 million tonnes in 2000 and peaking at 500 million tonnes in 2010. After 2010, the emissions saw a small decline, falling to 450 million tonnes by 2020.\n\nThis indicates an overall growth in CO2 output over three decades.
1f39431e-80a7-4b14-865f-c8c147c90179	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Ti├¬u Thß╗Ñ N╞░ß╗¢c To├án Cß║ºu	environment-ielts-task-1-global-water-usage-barchart	The bar chart below displays the proportion of water consumed by three main sectors: agriculture, industry, and domestic use, in Country A and Country B in 2015.\n\n[Imagine a bar chart:\nCountry A: Agriculture ~70%, Industry ~15%, Domestic ~15%\nCountry B: Agriculture ~40%, Industry ~30%, Domestic ~30%]\n\nSummarize the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant. Write at least 80 words.	M├┤ tß║ú biß╗âu ─æß╗ô cß╗Öt so s├ính l╞░ß╗úng n╞░ß╗¢c ti├¬u thß╗Ñ trong ba l─⌐nh vß╗▒c ch├¡nh (n├┤ng nghiß╗çp, c├┤ng nghiß╗çp, sinh hoß║ít) ß╗ƒ hai quß╗æc gia kh├íc nhau v├áo n─âm 2015.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_1	2	t	2026-07-16 19:03:44.224	2026-07-16 19:03:44.224	20	\N	0	The bar chart shows how much water was used in agriculture, industry, and homes in Country A and Country B in 2015.\n\nOverall, Country A used significantly more water for agriculture than Country B, where water consumption was more evenly spread across sectors.\n\nIn Country A, agriculture accounted for the largest share of water use, at about 70%. Industry and domestic use were much lower, both around 15%.\n\nIn contrast, Country BΓÇÖs water consumption was distributed differently. Agriculture used 40%, while industry and domestic sectors each consumed around 30% of the total water.
7c0ee2fa-7b3c-4429-b7f3-7a9d9d403358	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Th├ánh Phß║ºn R├íc Thß║úi Sinh Hoß║ít	environment-ielts-task-1-household-waste-composition-piechart	The pie chart below illustrates the different types of household waste produced in a particular city in 2022.\n\n[Imagine a pie chart:\nOrganic Waste: 35%\nPaper/Cardboard: 25%\nPlastics: 20%\nGlass: 10%\nMetals: 5%\nOthers: 5%]\n\nSummarize the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant. Write at least 80 words.	M├┤ tß║ú biß╗âu ─æß╗ô tr├▓n vß╗ü c├íc loß║íi r├íc thß║úi sinh hoß║ít ─æ╞░ß╗úc tß║ío ra trong mß╗Öt th├ánh phß╗æ cß╗Ñ thß╗â v├áo n─âm 2022.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_1	3	t	2026-07-16 19:03:44.24	2026-07-16 19:03:44.24	20	\N	0	The pie chart presents the composition of household waste in a specific city during 2022.\n\nOverall, organic waste was the largest component, followed by paper and plastics, while glass, metals, and other waste types made up smaller proportions.\n\nOrganic waste comprised the highest percentage, at 35% of the total. Paper and cardboard together formed the second largest category, accounting for 25%. Plastics contributed 20% to the total waste.\n\nThe remaining categories were smaller: glass made up 10%, and both metals and 'others' each accounted for 5% of the household waste.
f7dafe9f-da98-41f9-b8f9-513d3f206478	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Xu H╞░ß╗¢ng Ph├í Rß╗½ng Khu Vß╗▒c	environment-ielts-task-1-regional-deforestation-table	The table below shows the annual deforestation rates (in percentage) in three different regions: Amazon, Southeast Asia, and Central Africa, for the years 2000 and 2010.\n\n[Imagine a table:\nRegion          2000 (%)    2010 (%)\nAmazon          0.5         0.3\nSoutheast Asia  1.2         0.8\nCentral Africa  0.7         0.6]\n\nSummarize the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant. Write at least 80 words.	M├┤ tß║ú bß║úng sß╗æ liß╗çu vß╗ü tß╗╖ lß╗ç ph├í rß╗½ng h├áng n─âm ß╗ƒ ba khu vß╗▒c kh├íc nhau (Amazon, ─É├┤ng Nam ├ü, Trung Phi) v├áo n─âm 2000 v├á 2010.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_1	4	t	2026-07-16 19:03:44.265	2026-07-16 19:03:44.265	20	\N	0	The table displays the annual rates of deforestation in three regions: the Amazon, Southeast Asia, and Central Africa, in 2000 and 2010.\n\nOverall, deforestation rates decreased in all three regions from 2000 to 2010, with Southeast Asia consistently having the highest rates.\n\nIn 2000, Southeast Asia had the highest deforestation rate at 1.2%, followed by Central Africa at 0.7%, and the Amazon region at 0.5%.\n\nBy 2010, all regions showed a reduction. Southeast Asia's rate fell to 0.8%, while Central Africa's decreased to 0.6%. The Amazon region also saw a decline, dropping to 0.3%. Despite the improvements, Southeast Asia still faced the most significant deforestation challenge.
1d4dc4e0-573e-4e5f-b0b5-b66b21a36fb8	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Quy Tr├¼nh T├íi Chß║┐ N╞░ß╗¢c	environment-ielts-task-1-water-recycling-process-diagram	The diagram below illustrates the process of recycling wastewater into clean water.\n\n[Imagine a simplified process diagram:\n1. Wastewater collected -> 2. Screening (remove large items) -> 3. Primary Treatment (settling tanks, remove solids) -> 4. Secondary Treatment (aeration, bacteria eat waste) -> 5. Tertiary Treatment (filtration, disinfection with UV/Chlorine) -> 6. Clean Water ready for use]\n\nSummarize the information by describing the stages of the process and how they lead to the production of clean water. Write at least 80 words.	M├┤ tß║ú s╞í ─æß╗ô minh hß╗ìa quy tr├¼nh t├íi chß║┐ n╞░ß╗¢c thß║úi th├ánh n╞░ß╗¢c sß║ích, bao gß╗ôm c├íc giai ─æoß║ín ch├¡nh.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_1	5	t	2026-07-16 19:03:44.283	2026-07-16 19:03:44.283	20	\N	0	The diagram shows the six-stage process of turning wastewater into clean water for reuse.\n\nOverall, the process begins with collecting wastewater and involves several treatment steps, including physical, biological, and chemical methods, to ensure the water is clean.\n\nFirst, wastewater is collected and then goes through screening to remove large objects. Next, in primary treatment, the water enters settling tanks where solid waste separates. Following this, secondary treatment uses aeration and bacteria to break down remaining waste.\n\nAfter these stages, tertiary treatment involves filtering the water and disinfecting it with UV light or chlorine. Finally, the treated water is ready to be used again.
a43cf8a3-53e1-484b-b0af-a523ecc6f121	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Causes and Effects of Environmental Pollution	environment-ielts-task2-causes-effects-pollution	Ng├áy nay, ├┤ nhiß╗àm m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng l├á mß╗Öt vß║Ñn ─æß╗ü nghi├¬m trß╗ìng tr├¬n to├án cß║ºu. H├úy viß║┐t mß╗Öt b├ái luß║¡n vß╗ü c├íc nguy├¬n nh├ón ch├¡nh g├óy ra ├┤ nhiß╗àm m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng v├á nhß╗»ng hß║¡u quß║ú m├á n├│ g├óy ra cho h├ánh tinh cß╗ºa ch├║ng ta. Bß║ín n├¬n ─æ╞░a ra ├¡t nhß║Ñt hai nguy├¬n nh├ón v├á hai hß║¡u quß║ú.	Viß║┐t vß╗ü c├íc nguy├¬n nh├ón v├á hß║¡u quß║ú cß╗ºa ├┤ nhiß╗àm m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_2	1	t	2026-07-16 19:04:02.243	2026-07-16 19:04:02.243	20	\N	0	Environmental pollution is a big problem today. There are many reasons for it. First, factories produce a lot of smoke and waste materials, which pollute the air and water. Second, cars release harmful gases, especially in cities, leading to smog. People also throw rubbish everywhere, damaging the land and oceans. These actions have serious effects. Air pollution causes respiratory diseases for humans and animals. Water pollution makes rivers and lakes unsafe for drinking and kills marine life. Plastic waste also harms animals. We must find solutions, like using cleaner energy and recycling more, to protect our environment for the future.
346fdb17-9341-431a-afc5-1774d06d977c	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	The Importance of Recycling for Environmental Protection	environment-ielts-task2-importance-recycling	T├íi chß║┐ l├á mß╗Öt h├ánh ─æß╗Öng ─æ╞ín giß║ún nh╞░ng c├│ thß╗â tß║ío ra t├íc ─æß╗Öng lß╗¢n ─æß║┐n m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng. H├úy viß║┐t mß╗Öt b├ái luß║¡n thß║úo luß║¡n vß╗ü tß║ºm quan trß╗ìng cß╗ºa viß╗çc t├íi chß║┐ v├á giß║úi th├¡ch c├ích n├│ gi├║p bß║úo vß╗ç h├ánh tinh cß╗ºa ch├║ng ta.	Thß║úo luß║¡n vß╗ü tß║ºm quan trß╗ìng cß╗ºa viß╗çc t├íi chß║┐ v├á c├ích n├│ gi├║p bß║úo vß╗ç m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_2	2	t	2026-07-16 19:04:02.258	2026-07-16 19:04:02.258	20	\N	0	Recycling is very important for our planet. When we recycle, we turn old items into new ones. This means we use fewer new materials from the Earth. For example, recycling paper saves trees, and recycling plastic reduces the need for new oil. It also helps reduce the amount of waste that goes into landfills. Landfills take up a lot of space and can pollute the soil and air. By recycling, we also save energy because making products from recycled materials often uses less energy than making them from scratch. Everyone should try to recycle more paper, plastic, glass, and metal to protect our beautiful environment.
69e2a088-3378-470f-b4c5-0b6b9257a1d7	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Who is Responsible for Protecting the Environment?	environment-ielts-task2-responsibility-environment	Mß╗Öt sß╗æ ng╞░ß╗¥i tin rß║▒ng ch├¡nh phß╗º c├│ tr├ích nhiß╗çm ch├¡nh trong viß╗çc bß║úo vß╗ç m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng, trong khi nhß╗»ng ng╞░ß╗¥i kh├íc ngh─⌐ rß║▒ng c├í nh├ón mß╗ùi ng╞░ß╗¥i n├¬n chß╗ïu tr├ích nhiß╗çm. H├úy viß║┐t mß╗Öt b├ái luß║¡n thß║úo luß║¡n cß║ú hai quan ─æiß╗âm n├áy v├á ─æ╞░a ra ├╜ kiß║┐n cß╗ºa bß║ín.	Tranh luß║¡n vß╗ü tr├ích nhiß╗çm cß╗ºa ch├¡nh phß╗º v├á c├í nh├ón trong viß╗çc bß║úo vß╗ç m├┤i tr╞░ß╗¥ng.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_2	3	t	2026-07-16 19:04:02.266	2026-07-16 19:04:02.266	20	\N	0	Protecting the environment is a big task, and people have different ideas about who should do it. Some believe governments should lead because they can make laws and big policies. For example, governments can ban harmful chemicals or invest in renewable energy. They can also fund environmental clean-up projects. However, others argue that individuals also have a huge role. Simple actions like reducing waste, recycling, saving energy, and choosing eco-friendly products all make a difference. If everyone takes personal responsibility, the collective impact would be very strong. I think both are important. Governments should set the rules, but individuals must follow them and contribute daily to protect our planet.
63b46975-d5c3-4c4d-ad86-bd5532922b55	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Impact of Climate Change on Our Daily Lives	environment-ielts-task2-impact-climate-change	Biß║┐n ─æß╗òi kh├¡ hß║¡u ─æang trß╗ƒ th├ánh mß╗Öt th├ích thß╗⌐c lß╗¢n tr├¬n to├án cß║ºu. H├úy viß║┐t mß╗Öt b├ái luß║¡n vß╗ü mß╗Öt sß╗æ t├íc ─æß╗Öng ch├¡nh cß╗ºa biß║┐n ─æß╗òi kh├¡ hß║¡u ─æß║┐n cuß╗Öc sß╗æng h├áng ng├áy cß╗ºa ch├║ng ta v├á ─æß╗ü xuß║Ñt mß╗Öt giß║úi ph├íp nhß╗Å m├á c├í nh├ón c├│ thß╗â l├ám.	Viß║┐t vß╗ü t├íc ─æß╗Öng cß╗ºa biß║┐n ─æß╗òi kh├¡ hß║¡u ─æß║┐n cuß╗Öc sß╗æng h├áng ng├áy cß╗ºa ch├║ng ta.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_2	4	t	2026-07-16 19:04:02.281	2026-07-16 19:04:02.281	20	\N	0	Climate change is affecting everyone, and its impacts are visible in our daily lives. One major impact is more extreme weather. We see stronger storms, longer droughts, and heavier rains, which can damage homes and crops. For example, some areas face hotter summers and colder winters. This also affects food prices, as farming becomes more difficult in changing climates. Another impact is on health. Air pollution from burning fossil fuels, which contributes to climate change, can cause breathing problems. To help, individuals can make small changes. For instance, we can use less electricity by turning off lights, or walk and bike more instead of driving. These small steps can collectively reduce our carbon footprint and help our planet.
c45bf89b-85f3-44d2-8073-b09c18b53ed5	5a5f69d1-b29d-48ad-bac3-e0898fc7820b	Promoting Public Transport to Reduce Pollution	environment-ielts-task2-public-transport-pollution	Viß╗çc sß╗¡ dß╗Ñng ├┤ t├┤ c├í nh├ón ng├áy c├áng nhiß╗üu ─æang g├│p phß║ºn v├áo ├┤ nhiß╗àm kh├┤ng kh├¡ v├á tß║»c nghß║╜n giao th├┤ng ß╗ƒ c├íc th├ánh phß╗æ lß╗¢n. H├úy viß║┐t mß╗Öt b├ái luß║¡n vß╗ü lß╗úi ├¡ch cß╗ºa viß╗çc khuyß║┐n kh├¡ch ng╞░ß╗¥i d├ón sß╗¡ dß╗Ñng ph╞░╞íng tiß╗çn giao th├┤ng c├┤ng cß╗Öng v├á ─æß╗ü xuß║Ñt mß╗Öt c├ích ─æß╗â l├ám ─æiß╗üu n├áy hiß╗çu quß║ú h╞ín.	Thß║úo luß║¡n vß╗ü lß╗úi ├¡ch cß╗ºa viß╗çc khuyß║┐n kh├¡ch sß╗¡ dß╗Ñng ph╞░╞íng tiß╗çn giao th├┤ng c├┤ng cß╗Öng ─æß╗â giß║úm ├┤ nhiß╗àm.	80	150	B1	IELTS_TASK_2	5	t	2026-07-16 19:04:02.289	2026-07-16 19:04:02.289	20	\N	0	Using public transport more often can bring many benefits, especially for reducing pollution in cities. When more people use buses, trains, or subways, fewer private cars are on the road. This means less exhaust fumes enter the air, which improves air quality and helps reduce health problems like asthma. Also, it helps reduce traffic jams, making travel faster for everyone. To encourage more people to use public transport, cities could make it cheaper or even free. They could also improve the quality of public transport by making it more frequent, comfortable, and reliable. For example, adding more routes to cover more areas would be helpful. Making public transport attractive and convenient will lead to fewer cars and a cleaner environment.
